{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11441"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.18,0.37,0.08,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4075"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78883"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4075"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33172"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78883"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously healthy 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner complaining of a cough with blood-tinged sputum and shortness of breath at rest. This has been progressively worsening over the past week. She had a caesarean delivery two months ago due to fetal distress at 36 weeks gestation. She reports no difficulty with baby care, breastfeeding, bladder or bowel function. The lower transverse caesarean section incision is healing well. She had some vaginal bleeding last week. Her vital signs are unremarkable. The fundal height is 20 cm and pelvic examination shows some vaginal bleeding. A chest X-ray shows multiple pulmonary nodules with circumscribed margins seen in both lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Further evaluation is most likely to reveal which one of the following findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acid fast bacilli in sputum","DVT on lower limb doppler","Increased serum \u03b2-hCG levels","Elevated parathyroid hormone-related peptide","Positive aspergillus IgG serology"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Echoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E which is a highly aggressive, malignant tumour consisting of trophoblastic tissue. The only way it can develop is after fertilisation and implantation of the egg (e.g. normal or ectopic pregnancy, hydatidiform mole, miscarriage). This malignancy has a \u003Cstrong\u003Etendency to metastasize to the lungs\u003C/strong\u003E via haematogenous spread). Positive findings in this patient include a history of pregnancy, postpartum vaginal bleeding, inadequate regression of the uterus, and signs of metastases to the lungs and \u0022cannonball\u0022 appearance on the chest X-ray. The initial test of choice is \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum b-HCG which is often very high\u003C/strong\u003E (sometimes higher than 1000 U/mL). It is usually treated with methotrexate and has a good prognosis. After treatment, follow-up hCG monitoring every month for at least 12 months is essential for surveillance of relapse. Reliable contraception must be used throughout this period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcid fast bacilli in sputum\u003C/strong\u003E are found in cases of pulmonary tuberculosis. Progressive dyspnea and hemoptysis in the context of TB may indicate extensive lung parenchymal involvement. However, this patient does not have any systemic signs (e.g. fever, night sweats, weight loss) to indicate chronic course. Chest X-ray findings in TB may include consolidation, Ghon complex, lesions in the upper lobes, and unilateral hilar lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis (DVT) on lower limb doppler\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely consideration in this case. Certainly deep vein thrombosis can be complicated by pulmonary embolism. Whilst not alway present, many patients with a pulmonary embolism will have clinical suspicion of a DVT (pain, swelling, warmth and redness in the affected limb). However, these classic symptoms are not present in this particular case, and the respiratory symptoms described and the radiological findings are not indicative of a pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated parathyroid hormone-related peptide\u003C/strong\u003E may indicate a lung squamous cell carcinoma. This is a centrally located solid epithelial tumour that is highly associated with smoking. It may present with hemoptysis if the tumour invades the bronchi. However, these are infrequently found on chest X-ray and if present they may appear as bulky hilum and lobar collapse - this is not the case in this patient. As a general rule, primary lung cancer usually has a single nodule with irregular margins compared to the multiple \u0022cannonball\u0022 nodules of lung metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive aspergillus IgG serology\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in cases of chronic pulmonary aspergillosis which can present with haemoptysis, dyspnoea, and multiple nodules on chest X-ray. However, it usually occurs in patients with long term aspergillus infection. Risk factors for aspergillosis include immunosuppression, chronic granulomatous disease, chronic destructive lung disease, and alcohol use disorder - none of which are present in this patient. Moreover, it would present with systemic symptoms (e.g. fatigue, weight loss, fever) which are also absent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postpartum vaginal bleeding, inadequate regression of the uterus, and metastatic lesions on chest X-ray are suggestive of underlying choriocarcinoma.","Choriocarcinoma is a malignant trophoblastic tumour that can develop after any type of pregnancy and is characterised by elevated serum \u03b2-hCG levels.","Choriocarcinoma has a high propensity for haematogenous spread, commonly metastasising to the lungs, which can present as multiple pulmonary nodules on imaging."],"references":["Quade, BJ. Gestational trophoblastic disease: Pathology and genetics. [Internet]. UptoDate. 2024 Dec. Accessed on 2025 Jan 13. Available from:  https://www.uptodate.com/contents/gestational-trophoblastic-disease-pathology","Knipe, H. Diffuse pulmonary nodules. [Internet]. Radiopedia. 2024 Oct. Accessed on 2025 Jan 13. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/diffuse-pulmonary-nodules","Williams A. Differential diagnosis of elevated human chorionic gonadotropin in women. Case Rep Womens Health. 2022 Nov 30;37:e00471. doi: 10.1016/j.crwh.2022.e00471. PMID: 37064211; PMCID: PMC10101843. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10101843/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64232"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T10:18:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T10:20:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"